Here's the approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove any existing theme dictionary
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Themes.LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
        else
            ApplyTheme(AppTheme.Light);
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** Have each theme XAML's code-behind implement a marker interface (`IThemeDictionary`) so you can identify and replace only the theme dictionary.

### 3. Consume theme resources with `DynamicResource`

This is the key — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 4. Wire it up

**App.xaml.cs** — apply saved theme at startup:
```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

**SettingsPage** — let the user pick:
```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding ThemeOptions}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var selected = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **`DynamicResource`** | Picks up dictionary swaps at runtime — `StaticResource` won't. |
| **`MergedDictionaries`** | Swap the entire theme dictionary in one operation. |
| **`Preferences`** | Persists the user's choice across app restarts. |
| **Consistent keys** | Every theme must define the same set of resource keys. |

This gives you instant, app-wide theme switching with no page reloads.
